0 'STARTER TRIBUTE'~
None~
0 1 none
When you join a new clan you will receive starter tribute based on your hours
played and position in your previous clan.  Unfortunately, it's impossible
to determine what each individual contributed exactly, so everyone is fairly
well rewarded -- in the case of very rich clans, the long time members will
receive more than members of other clans.  Remember that as time goes on, this
bonus will pale in comparison to the tribute clan members can bring in -- and
new members will never reduce the tribute you have available.  So don't count
it against someone to not have a lot of starter tribute.

Starter tribute is intended to let you get a running start with a new clan, but
it is not intended to set you up to never have to earn tribute again.  For this
reason, when anyone with any amount of starter tribute begins a clan, they
receive a flat 20000 tribute bonus separate from their starter tribute.  If a
player is very newly created, they will not have any starter tribute points.
They will have received a starter tribute credit instead, which entitles them
to the 20000 tribute point bonus if they start a clan, but no bonuses past it.
To both provide a suitable reward for older, experienced players while not
allowing people to grab half the mud into their clan and get unreasonable
amounts of tribute, the following scaling has been set up:

The highest starter tribute value is at 100%.  The second highest is at 75%.
The third highest is at 60%.  The fourth highest is at 50%.  This continues on
forever, slowly reducing the bonuses.  This recalculates every time someone
joins or leaves the clan (You can be driven to negative tribute if you spend a
lot and a high-tribute member leaves).

An example: If someone has 2000 starter tribute and begins a clan, they will
have 22000 tribute available.  If a new member joins with 5000 tribute, the
clan will have 26500 tribute -- 20000 + 5000 * 100% + 2000 * 75%.  If the first
player then leaves, the tribute would drop to 25000 as they took their starter
tribute with them (Plus any donated in the meantime -- that does not get taken
away).  As detailed below, this starter tribute transfer out of the clan is
temporary to allow flexibility.

The maximum amount of starting tribute a clan can get is 20000, which leaves
them at double the base amount.  The highest starting tribute a single player
can possibly reach is 10000.  Note that only a few players will qualify for
this amount, but others can compensate by inviting some experienced friends to
their clan for the additive bonus -- reaching the cap is just noticably easier
if you start with a higher value, rewarding your experience with flexibility.

{WNote{x: Starter tribute will not always stay locked to your character, that
is a temporary measure to allow people to more freely switch clans while they
are seeing what the new system involves, and is not expected to last more than
a couple months.  When it is changed, you will not lose your starter tribute
but it will be permanently locked into the clan you are in.  {YThere will be
warning before this happens.{x  At that point, newly created characters (Level
20 and lower joining the clan system) will also stop gaining starter tribute.

Also see:
help tribute
help clan
~
0 'MERIT' 'TRIBUTE'~
None~
0 1 none
Tribute to the gods is required to enhance your clan.  It is obtained by
earning merit, then donating the merit.

Killing mobs.  If the mob grants you experience, you can earn merit for
  killing it.  The amount of merit is based on the mob's level, with higher
  enemies giving noticably higher amounts.  Note that having charmies involved
  in the kill will reduce the amount of merit received.  Multiple players
  will split merit based on normal experience rules.

Killing players.  When you kill a player, their currently carried merit is
  completely removed from them and transferred to everyone involved in the kill
  based on the amount of damage each did to the victim.  The killer receives
  the normal kill bonus amount as well, appropriate to the level of the victim.
  The player landing the kill will receive the full merit bonus, a player
  kill does not split.  Charmies will not reduce this bonus.  A player that has
  died recently will not award as much tribute as one that has been alive for a
  longer time.

Stealing from players.  A thief may "steal merit" from an enemy and will then
  attempt a difficult steal to demonstrate to the gods that they are worthy of
  some of the merit their victim has gathered.  A player may only lose up to
  15% of their donation amount per hour to theft.

Completing quests.  There will be automatic quests that will grant some tribute
  upon completion.  {YThese do not exist yet.{x

Once you have earned enough merit, you may donate it.  The amount you donate at
once is based on your level.  If you do not have at least this much, you can
not donate it.  100 merit is worth 1 tribute, which is what clan costs are
measured in.

  Level 5:  100   (1 tribute)
  Level 11: 400
  Level 21: 1,600
  Level 31: 3,600
  Level 41: 6,400
  Level 51: 10,000 (100 tribute)

If you are in a clan, all merit you have donated automatically goes into the
clan's tribute pool.  If you are not in a clan, you'll have a personal pool
that you will build, and when you join a clan it will be added to theirs.

Merit and tribute are clan currencies only.

Also see:
help donate
help prices
help offer
~
