Use edithelp (Or ehelp) to edit help files.  When done, be sure to use save.
Available commands are:
ehelp new (Creates a new file)
ehelp edit (Selects a file to edit)
ehelp list <keyword> (Lists files with matching keywords)
ehelp editor <name> lists any helpfiles edited by the exact player <name>
ehelp sort <status> (Lists files with matching statuses)
Available status options: Legacy, draft, review, final.  Legacy means the
  help file has not been modified with the new system.  Draft help files
  will not display on live.  Review and Final both will transfer to live.
* Any commands after this point require you be editing a help file to use. *
ehelp show (Shows current help file)
ehelp details (Editing information on current help file)
ehelp text (Edits the help file's main text)
ehelp level (Sets the help file's level. Use -1 to hide the green bars)
* Use of -1 should be kept to things like motd where the bars are
  inappropriate. Most help files should be at 0 or higher. *
ehelp keywords <keywords> (Sets help file's keywords. 'keys' works too)
ehelp status <status> (Sets the help file's status. Draft, review, or final)
ehelp related <related> (Sets what help files are related to the current)
ehelp save (Saves your current work)
ehelp discard (Undoes your current work, reloads original file)
ehelp delete <keyword> (Deletes currently edited file. Be careful with this)
ehelp done (Stop using ehelp)
~
55 'EHELP STANDARDS' 'EDITHELP STANDARDS'~
Ehelp~
1358306623 1 Andaron
Editing helpfiles comes with a responsibility to make good changes. The last
person to edit a helpfile will have their name recorded with it -- if you
find a helpfile that is inappropriate, you should discard any changes you
have made (If you save you become the last to modify it) and talk to an
appropriate admin about the issue.

Setting the level of the helpfile should be done to match the intended
audience.  If it's immortals only, it should be level 52.  If it's only
builders and higher, it should be level 55.  Level -1 will make the helpfile
not show the header and footer, but should be reserved only for special
helpfiles such as the wizlist.

Legacy status is only intended for helpfiles that have not been edited, and
upon first save a helpfile will move from Legacy to Review (If you do not
set it manually).  Draft status will NOT show on live, so should be used
only for new helpfiles, or help files that you don't want to be viewable
(Because they're not relevant currently, or for any similar reason.) Review
status will indicate to other imms that you would like the helpfile reviewed
but that you feel it's good enough to go live as it is.  So review will show
up on live.  Final status means that you feel it's done as it is, and it
will go live.

Take responsibility for your edits, make the helpfiles useful, and everyone
will be happy.
~
